        "\n",
        "# Module 2: Measurement Model Verification\n",
        "\n",
        "This module confirms that the survey items used to measure constructs like \"Brand Image\" or \"Function\" are actually measuring what they intend to.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Section 1: Internal Consistency\n",
        "\n",
        "### Objective\n",
        "To calculate Cronbach’s Alpha for each construct to confirm that the items within a group are reliable.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Statistical Perspective\n",
        "\n",
        "**Internal Consistency & Reliability:** Reliability is the core foundation of psychometric measurement. It essentially assesses the absence of random error mathematically. If an individual respondent truthfully has a highly positive psychological orientation toward \"Brand Image,\" they should subsequently score highly on *all* questions intended to measure that Brand Image. If answers fluctuate wildly within the same psychological construct, the scale is completely unreliable.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Cronbach’s Alpha ($\\alpha$):**\n",
        "This is the universally accepted standard metric that calculates the average pairwise correlation among all structural items measuring a specific construct.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Criteria Standards:** $\\alpha \\ge 0.70$ is generally considered acceptable in exploratory management research. $\\alpha \\ge 0.80$ is classified as definitively good, and $\\alpha \\ge 0.90$ is excellent. If $\\alpha < 0.60$, the construct items must be fundamentally revised or discarded entirely.\n",
        "- **Parametric Assumption:** This rigid metric assumes *unidimensionality* (that all the aggregated items mathematically map to one and only one underlying latent psychological variable). It also assumes $\\tau$-equivalence, where each item contributes equally to the true score.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Industry Application:** Human Resources departments rely on internal consistency when purchasing expensive aptitude assessments for hiring. If a leadership questionnaire has an alpha of $0.50$, it's mathematical junk, meaning candidates could get completely different scores simply by taking it again tomorrow.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Python Example Code"
      ],
      "id": "453d45b8"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
