        "\n",
        "## Section 4: Common Method Bias\n",
        "\n",
        "### Objective\n",
        "To perform Harman’s Single Factor Test to ensure one single factor does not account for the majority of the variance.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Statistical Perspective\n",
        "Because empirical respondents generally provide data for both the independent variables (IV) and dependent variables (DV) simultaneously in a single cross-sectional survey instrument, massive artificial correlations might exist simply due to the measurement method (e.g., the mood of the respondent, the wording of the questionnaire, or general survey fatigue), rather than any true causal psychological relationship.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Harman’s Single Factor Test:**\n",
        "This is the classical diagnostic approach to diagnosing Common Method Variance (CMV). It violently forces all structural survey items into an unrotated Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to determine the baseline dimensionality.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Criteria Limits:** If a single unrotated principal component emerges that explains over $50\\%$ of the total cumulative variance in the dataset, Common Method Bias is deemed severe. It implies the survey method itself is driving the responses, not the theoretical constructs.\n",
        "- **Consequences:** If bias is severe, the researcher must physically re-administer the survey with procedural remedies (e.g., separating the IV and DV with a time delay, guaranteeing strict anonymity, or using mixed methods like objective secondary data).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Industry Application:** In employee performance evaluations, if \"Self-Rated Leadership,\" \"Self-Rated Teamwork,\" and \"Self-Rated Productivity\" are assessed concurrently, an employee's ego acts as a common method bias, inflating all metrics simultaneously and making the data useless for HR promotions.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Python Example Code"
      ],
