        "\n",
        "# Module 3: Structural Path Modeling\n",
        "\n",
        "This module identifies which factors significantly influence satisfaction and loyalty.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Section 1: Path Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "### Objective\n",
        "To construct a model where Function, Usability, Price, and Brand Image lead to Customer Satisfaction, which leads to Loyalty.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Statistical Perspective\n",
        "Path analysis is an extension of multiple regression that allows researchers to visually and computationally evaluate a holistic system of equations simultaneously. Rather than isolating individual regressions, we calculate multi-step directional sequences (e.g., Brand Image $\\rightarrow$ Satisfaction $\\rightarrow$ Loyalty).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Assumptions in Path Modeling:**\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Linearity & Additivity:** The true relationships between constructs are linear.\n",
        "2. **No Endogeneity:** Error terms ($\\epsilon$) are mutually independent, and no unmeasured variable is lurking in the background silently driving both the IV and the DV.\n",
        "3. **Causal Directionality:** The flow of arrows is grounded in robust theoretical reasoning (e.g., temporal logic dictates that observing Brand Image inherently precedes the psychological feeling of Customer Satisfaction, not vice versa).\n",
        "4. **Recursive Relationships:** Feedback loops (where Satisfaction feeds back into Brand Image in an endless cycle) are notoriously hard to model accurately and are explicitly avoided in standard baseline SEM.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Industry Application:** In the airline industry, operations teams map structural paths to determine if \"Flight Punctuality\" impacts \"Baggage Claim Satisfaction\" directly, or if it purely alters global \"Overall Brand Trust\", dictating exactly where they should dedicate ground staff resources.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Python Example Code"
      ],
