        "\n",
        "## Section 2: Hypothesis Testing\n",
        "\n",
        "### Objective\n",
        "To evaluate the p-values and t-statistics to definitively conclude which factors significantly affect satisfaction.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Statistical Perspective\n",
        "Hypothesis testing uses empirical sample data to decide mathematically whether to definitively reject a pre-defined null hypothesis (e.g., $H_0$: \"Brand Image has strictly NO true effect on Customer Satisfaction in the general population\").\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Statistical Criteria:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- **p-value ($p$):** The quantitative probability of observing the surveyed data (or something more extreme) if the null hypothesis were absolutely true under the curve. We reject $H_0$ firmly if $p < 0.05$ (establishing a 95% confidence level), or $p < 0.01$ (99% confidence level).\n",
        "- **t-statistic ($t$):** Measures the absolute size of the estimated coefficient difference relative to the inherent standard error variation in the sample data. The criterion for statistical significance is typically $t > 1.96$ or $t < -1.96$ for a two-tailed probability test.\n",
        "- **Statistical Power ($1 - \\beta$):** Having $n=208$ respondents helps guarantee that if there actually *is* an effect to be found in the reality of Taiwan's scooter market, our mathematical test has the \"power\" to successfully detect it without returning a false negative (Type II error).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Industry Application:** In pharmaceutical trials, Hypothesis Testing dictates whether a million-dollar drug receives FDA approval ($p<0.05$) or gets binned into oblivion ($p>0.05$). The rules are rigid specifically to prevent dangerous false-positive inferences.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Python Example Code"
      ],
