        "\n",
        "## Section 3: Impact Ranking\n",
        "\n",
        "### Objective\n",
        "To compare Standardized Beta Coefficients ($\\beta$) to establish that Brand Image influences satisfaction the most.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Statistical Perspective\n",
        "When variables are measured on wildly different psychometric units or simply to ascertain strictly relative structural importance, **Standardized Beta Coefficients ($\\beta$)** are inherently used. The process physically rescales the raw data matrix entirely via Z-scores, so every measured variable has a mean of exactly 0 and a deterministic standard deviation of precisely 1.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Mathematical Interpretation & Strict Criteria:**\n",
        "- A resulting coefficient of $\\beta = 0.45$ mathematically dictates that for every 1 standard deviation ($1\\sigma$) increase in the independent predictor, the dependent variable reliably increases by exactly 0.45 standard deviations ($0.45\\sigma$).\n",
        "- By directly comparing the absolute magnitude of $\\beta$ values, researchers can decisively rank the empirical importance of each strategic predictor side-by-side. For instance, if $\\beta_{BrandImage} = 0.60$ and $\\beta_{Function} = 0.20$, Brand Image is empirically confirmed as the $3\\times$ stronger causal driver of ultimate user satisfaction.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Industry Application:** A political campaign mathematically calculates standardized betas on their polling surveys. If the $\\beta$ for \"Economic Policy\" is $0.55$, but the $\\beta$ for \"Foreign Policy\" is only $0.12$, the campaign will ruthlessly cut all advertising budget regarding foreign affairs and focus $100\\%$ on economics to maximize voter satisfaction.\n",
        "\n",
