        "\n",
        "## Section 4: Model Fit Indices\n",
        "\n",
        "### Objective\n",
        "To assess how well the theoretical path model fits the data using regression metrics like $R^2$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Statistical Perspective\n",
        "Model fit mathematically describes how well your theoretical statistical architecture actually represents the raw covariance matrix derived from the data. If the model fits poorly, any p-values or beta-paths internal to the model are mathematically dubious.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Regression Metrics:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- **$R^2$ (Coefficient of Determination):** Indicates the absolute proportion of variance inside the dependent variable globally explained by the composite sum of all included IVs. (E.g., $R^2 = 0.65$ means $65\\%$ of all reasons why people are satisfied are captured in the model).\n",
        "- **Adjusted $R^2$:** Standard $R^2$ artificially inflates purely by throwing garbage variables randomly into the equation. Adjusted $R^2$ explicitly penalizes the mathematical model equation for unnecessary complexity and bloat.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Structural Equation Modeling Metrics (SEM):**\n",
        "\n",
        "- **CFI (Comparative Fit Index):** Compares your model to a broken \"null\" model where nothing is correlated. The strict criterion is $CFI > 0.90$ (acceptable) or $> 0.95$ (excellent).\n",
        "- **RMSEA (Root Mean Square Error of Approximation):** Estimates the absolute lack of fit per degrees of freedom. The strict criterion demands $RMSEA < 0.08$ (acceptable) to guarantee that your theoretical arrows accurately map to human reality.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Industry Application:** In supply chain algorithm design at Amazon, researchers look obsessively at Adjusted metrics to avoid \"overfitting\" the logistical model to Christmas-season noise, ensuring $R^2$ represents genuine year-round demand drivers.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Python Example Code"
