        "\n",
        "### Evaluation Questions\n",
        "1. What is the difference between statistical significance vs practical significance?\n",
        "2. What does the $f^2$ metric evaluate?\n",
        "3. Why might a variable have a significant p-value but a very small effect size?\n",
        "4. What is the threshold for a 'large' effect size in $f^2$?\n",
        "5. How does omitting a variable help determine its importance?\n",
        "\n",
        "## Section 3: Predictive Relevance ($Q^2$)\n",
        "\n",
        "### Objective\n",
        "To use blindfolding or cross-validation to ensure the model has the power to predict loyalty in future users.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Statistical Perspective\n",
        "Structural models should not only explain historical patterns retroactively ($R^2$, known as explanatory power) but also mathematically predict future events proactively. **Predictive Relevance ($Q^2$)** specifically assesses how incredibly well the structural model quantitatively predicts completely isolated out-of-sample data points.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Blindfolding (k-fold Cross-Validation):**\n",
        "An automated, iterative computational process. The algorithmic model systematically deletes specific targeted data points in the empirical data matrix, natively estimates parameters based purely on the remaining points, and blindly attempts to statistically predict the omitted points based strictly on those constrained parameters.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Criteria & Diagnostic Boundaries:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- If **$Q^2 > 0$**: The mathematical model formally exhibits objective predictive relevance for a particular endogenous construct, meaning it accurately models real-world physics or psychology better than a pure random guess.\n",
        "- If **$Q^2 \\le 0$**: The computational model completely lacks out-of-sample predictive capacity and is severely overfitted to the training data. For corporate strategy, executing negative $Q^2$ policy decisions derived from the model is incredibly dangerous, akin to gambling blind.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Industry Application:** Machine Learning engineers at credit grading agencies like Equifax exclusively care about Out-of-Sample metrics like cross-validated $Q^2$. If a model explains the past crash perfectly ($R^2$) but fails to predict the next default ($Q^2 < 0$), it is financially useless.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Python Example Code"
      ],
      "id": "ffe7e9d1"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n",
        "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
        "\n",
        "df = pd.read_csv('gogoro_data.csv')\n",
        "X = df[['Brand1', 'Func1', 'Sat1']]\n",
